        <page n="01" image="pa.fr.vs.1860.05.30.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>Great Speech of Judge Douglas</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Douglas, in a transcript of a speech to the Senate, demonstrates how many
                    of the states and politicians who had withdrawn from the Democratic Convention
                    over the issue of popular sovereignty had in fact supported it in past
                    elections.</summary>
                <note>Speech takes up entire front page and jumps to next page.</note>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
        <page n="02" image="pa.fr.vs.1860.05.30.02">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>Douglas's Speech, continued</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Continuation of transcript of speech by Senator Douglas on the history of
                    political support for the doctrine of non-intervention.</summary>
                <note>Speech takes up entire page, and continues onto the next page.</note>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
        <page n="03" image="pa.fr.vs.1860.05.30.03">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>The President and the Editorial Visitors</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Story of a group of newspaper editors entertained at the White House by
                    President Buchanan, who made "brief but excellent" remarks on the necessity of
                    preserving the Union.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Advertisements, miscellaneous national news</pageNote>
        </page>
        <page n="04" image="pa.fr.vs.1860.05.30.04">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>The Democratic Party--It Must Be Preserved</head>
                <origin>Virginia Valley Democrat</origin>
                <commentary>Valley Spirit celebrates the union sentiment of a southern paper.</commentary>
                <excerpt>"And if [the Democratic Party] is maintained and guided by its own
                    landmarks, will be able to uphold the tottering temple of American freedom, and
                    successfully resist that Vandal horde of Black Republican fanatics, who are
                    marshalling their forces for 1860."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Emphasizes that the Democratic Party has upheld the rights of Southern
                    states, and insists that party unity is the only hope of maintaining national
                    unity and of fending off the Republicans.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Pennsylvanians Snubbed at Chicago</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Report from Republican National Convention in Chicago, where several
                    speakers derided Pennsylvania for naming its party "The People's Party" instead
                    of the "Republican Party."</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Fence Rails</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Asks that if Lincoln gained so much credit for having split rails 31 years
                    before with his friend John Shanks, then why shouldn't Shanks be running for
                    office as well?</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>05</column>
                <head>Political Intelligence</head>
                <origin>Detroit Free Press</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Alleges that many of the delegations to the Chicago Republican National
                    Convention were irregular--delegates were not from the states they purported to
                    be or were not even American citizens.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>05</column>
                <head>Political Intelligence</head>
                <origin>Boston Courier</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Argues that Lincoln's nomination has crippled the Republican Party.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>05</column>
                <head>Address to the National Democracy</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Circular addressed to the Democratic party, urging secessionist delegates
                    to postpone meeting at Richmond and return to the Baltimore Convention.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
